Iâ€™ve just finished my first week in anaesthetics and safe to say, I love it!
Iâ€™ve seen some super interesting cases this week. Monday (my first day) was a full day of gynae with a few quite large/long surgeries, resulting in post-op ICU admissions for two of the patients. I assisted with my first ever ETT intubation - got to push it in over the bougie (which was kinda scary but also really cool) and then blow up the cuff. A lot of the first day was just feeling a bit lost - I have the BEST buddy nurse working with me but I hate feeling like Iâ€™m in the way when I donâ€™t know where to stand or how to help out. I know once I learn the processes and what to expect â€˜nextâ€™ itâ€™ll be heaps easier.
Wednesday (my 2nd day) was a morning of orthopaedics - we saw two knee replacements and the surgeon gave me a piece of shaved-off knee (tibial surface to be precise) ğŸ˜‚ One side of it was healthy, spongy cartilage and the other side was the hard, diseased arthritic side. So cool to be able to see the effects of arthritis on the joint in real life - it really helps to understand disease processes when you can actually see how they effect the body. My buddy nurse took me through the anaesthetic machine check process and I had a couple practice runs. We had an early finish on Wednesday as our list wasnâ€™t long and we werenâ€™t needed in PACU afterwards.
On Thursday I came in a bit earlier to make sure I could check the anaesthetic machine and do the set up on my own - on the first two days my buddy nurse had beat me to it and I wanted to do it myself ğŸ˜‚ We started the morning with two gynae cases, and then finished the day with a small plastics case which was my first IV sedation, as the other surgeries Iâ€™d seen had all been under GA. We finished early again that day, but instead of going home I spent a couple hours with the theatre educator and we went through heaps of stuff which was super helpful. I did another anaesthetic machine check with her and we talked through all the parts of the machine, the different alarms, calibration, etc. To finish the day, she got me into a CAGS surgery [cont. in comments...]";}i:199;a:1:{s:14:"comments_count";i:3;}i:200;a:1:{s:11:"likes_count";i:31;}i:201;a:1:{s:4:"link";s:39:"https://www.instagram.com/p/CEvEdW3hzQH";}i:202;a:1:{s:5:"image";s:250:"https://scontent-sin6-2.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/s1080x1080/118808319_2709396619388949_8520238003356813827_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-sin6-2.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=109&_nc_ohc=HCUVHUbSAfAAX9S7bMT&oh=4692de9d12e39135d3b5314b8871a833&oe=5F7E2580";}i:203;a:1:{s:4:"type";s:5:"image";}i:204;a:1:{s:8:"owner_id";i:7825368856;}i:205;a:1:{s:14:"owner_username";s:0:"";}i:206;a:1:{s:14:"owner_fullname";s:0:"";}i:207;a:1:{s:9:"owner_pic";s:0:"";}i:208;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391148938285546136";}i:209;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEvEUpfj_qY";}i:210;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599267187;}i:211;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:113:"Iniciando um novo momento, em breve novidades! Fiquem atentos!! ğŸ¤©ğŸ©º

